WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.370 --> 00:00:12.100
- Good morning and welcome
to Radcliffe day 2017.

00:00:12.100 --> 00:00:17.770
And welcome to a lovely
spring day in New England.

00:00:17.770 --> 00:00:18.910
I'm Liz Cohen.

00:00:18.910 --> 00:00:21.970
I'm Dean of the Radcliffe
Institute for Advanced Study.

00:00:21.970 --> 00:00:25.290
I'm a professor of American
history here at Harvard,

00:00:25.290 --> 00:00:29.910
and, like many of you, I am
an avid and concerned consumer

00:00:29.910 --> 00:00:31.830
of the news.

00:00:31.830 --> 00:00:48.030
I am also a longtime admirer of
Gwen Ifill and Judy Woodruff,

00:00:48.030 --> 00:00:50.680
whom we will honor
with Radcliffe's metals

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:52.510
at today's lunch.

00:00:52.510 --> 00:00:56.620
By tradition, and by
design, this morning panel

00:00:56.620 --> 00:01:00.130
is devoted to a topic
that is close to the heads

00:01:00.130 --> 00:01:04.330
and hearts of our honorees,
often highlighting challenges

00:01:04.330 --> 00:01:07.180
in the area in which
they have excelled.

00:01:07.180 --> 00:01:11.800
Today's exploration, of
untruths and their consequences,

00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:16.180
will help us appreciate Gwen and
Judy's commitment to integrity

00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:19.330
in journalism all the more.

00:01:19.330 --> 00:01:24.070
Over a year ago, we decided
to focus this Radcliffe day

00:01:24.070 --> 00:01:27.640
on the changing media
landscape and to celebrate

00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:30.590
the best of journalism.

00:01:30.590 --> 00:01:36.530
When we began planning, the
phrase, alternative facts,

00:01:36.530 --> 00:01:42.290
was still an oxymoron and not
yet a fact of our existence,

00:01:42.290 --> 00:01:46.640
fake news was a
fringe phenomenon,

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:50.060
and the Oxford English
Dictionary had not yet

00:01:50.060 --> 00:01:57.470
designated post-truth as its
word of the year for 2016.

00:01:57.470 --> 00:02:02.690
Who, then, could imagine a
president of the United States

00:02:02.690 --> 00:02:07.460
accusing the mainstream
media of purveying fake news,

00:02:07.460 --> 00:02:10.440
and in a tweet,
calling the free press,

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:13.820
the enemy of the
American people?

00:02:13.820 --> 00:02:18.650
Presidents have long been
annoyed, even angered,

00:02:18.650 --> 00:02:21.470
by journalists,
but they have not

00:02:21.470 --> 00:02:25.190
depicted freedom of
the press as a threat

00:02:25.190 --> 00:02:27.980
to the very nation
that enshrines

00:02:27.980 --> 00:02:30.170
that ideal in its constitution.

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:42.490
Meanwhile, we are experiencing
equally dramatic changes

00:02:42.490 --> 00:02:45.520
in the ways that we
encounter the news.

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:47.710
A proliferation
of media sources,

00:02:47.710 --> 00:02:52.660
including Facebook, clickbait,
tweets, retweets, and memes,

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:55.600
has infiltrated
the news landscape.

00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:59.530
The dizzying number
and speed of new media

00:02:59.530 --> 00:03:02.590
challenge the
notion of authority,

00:03:02.590 --> 00:03:06.490
dismantle long standing
methods of quality control,

00:03:06.490 --> 00:03:10.000
and fragment American
audiences into narrow,

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:15.060
and often ideologically
defined, market segments.

00:03:15.060 --> 00:03:18.180
Tried and true media
like television news,

00:03:18.180 --> 00:03:21.990
frequently use similar
divide and conquer tactics.

00:03:21.990 --> 00:03:25.770
Networks know that there are
large potential audiences

00:03:25.770 --> 00:03:29.970
on the left, and the right, and
across all educational levels

00:03:29.970 --> 00:03:33.960
and income brackets, who want
their biases confirmed, not

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:38.460
challenged, by uncomfortable
or inconvenient facts.

00:03:38.460 --> 00:03:42.420
So, instead of sober and
meticulous reporting,

00:03:42.420 --> 00:03:47.250
we see panels of partisans who
substitute loudness of shouting

00:03:47.250 --> 00:03:49.380
for depth of analysis.

00:03:49.380 --> 00:03:53.190
Simplified messages might
entertain viewers and boost

00:03:53.190 --> 00:03:57.540
ratings, but they do not
provide the illuminating inquiry

00:03:57.540 --> 00:04:01.530
that an informed
electorate requires.

00:04:01.530 --> 00:04:03.900
And, yet, with
all the pandering,

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:06.780
a large proportion of
the American public

00:04:06.780 --> 00:04:11.910
still claims to deeply distrust
the media and the information

00:04:11.910 --> 00:04:13.620
it conveys.

00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:17.220
That distrust
should worry us all.

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:20.490
Whether the topic is
the fate of Obamacare,

00:04:20.490 --> 00:04:24.030
relations with Russia,
or climate change,

00:04:24.030 --> 00:04:28.380
only a well informed citizenry,
with a genuine understanding

00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:32.160
of the issues at stake,
can weigh opposing views

00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:34.800
and make smart and
fair decisions,

00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:38.910
with full appreciation of
the trade offs involved.

00:04:38.910 --> 00:04:42.030
A healthy, trusted
news media matters

00:04:42.030 --> 00:04:45.090
to all of us who care
about making the United

00:04:45.090 --> 00:04:49.860
States the robust, deliberative
democracy it has long

00:04:49.860 --> 00:04:51.000
aspired to be.

00:04:56.850 --> 00:05:00.560
How can we hope to live
up to those aspirations

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:04.280
with an embattled first
amendment, a besieged media,

00:05:04.280 --> 00:05:06.560
and an electorate
wandering in the wilderness

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:10.520
unable to distinguish
between truth and untruths?

00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:14.870
We are here today to probe
how we got here, but perhaps

00:05:14.870 --> 00:05:19.950
even more important, to ask
what we can do about it.

00:05:19.950 --> 00:05:23.600
We should also ask how
journalism and journalists can

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:25.970
respond to these challenges.

00:05:25.970 --> 00:05:28.880
I am cheered, for
example, that in the face

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:32.450
of the turmoil of the last
four months, and particularly

00:05:32.450 --> 00:05:35.700
over the astonishing
last few weeks,

00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:38.930
there have been journalists
who have remained undeterred,

00:05:38.930 --> 00:05:42.230
and even more determined,
to fulfill the press's

00:05:42.230 --> 00:05:47.180
constitutional responsibility
to pursue the truth wherever

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:49.430
it may take us.

00:05:49.430 --> 00:05:53.270
One of the ways that we tackle
big questions like these

00:05:53.270 --> 00:05:56.180
at the Radcliffe
Institute is by assembling

00:05:56.180 --> 00:06:00.290
stellar groups of individuals
to share experiences

00:06:00.290 --> 00:06:02.210
and expertise.

00:06:02.210 --> 00:06:05.870
We do so, all year long,
with lectures, conferences,

00:06:05.870 --> 00:06:09.710
and seminars, and
today is no exception.

00:06:09.710 --> 00:06:11.930
As an Institute
for advanced study,

00:06:11.930 --> 00:06:17.360
we know that deep research and
informed analysis do matter,

00:06:17.360 --> 00:06:21.590
and we value debate among
different perspectives as a way

00:06:21.590 --> 00:06:24.260
to move deliberation forward.

00:06:24.260 --> 00:06:26.690
This morning's discussion
brings together

00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:28.820
some of today's best minds.

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:32.570
Liberal, and conservative, from
the classroom, and the news

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:35.360
room, to help us
think through an issue

00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:39.500
that surely stands among the
most important challenges

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:42.980
our society faces
at this moment.

00:06:42.980 --> 00:06:45.140
To guide our
conversation today, we

00:06:45.140 --> 00:06:49.340
are fortunate to have my Harvard
colleague, Ann Marie Lipinski,

00:06:49.340 --> 00:06:51.040
as our moderator.

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:54.290
Ann Marie has won a Pulitzer
for her own investigative

00:06:54.290 --> 00:06:57.710
journalism, and has gone
on to award Pulitzers

00:06:57.710 --> 00:07:00.350
to others, first as
a member, and then

00:07:00.350 --> 00:07:03.990
as co-chair of the
Pulitzer Prize board.

00:07:03.990 --> 00:07:06.140
Ann Marie is
currently the curator

00:07:06.140 --> 00:07:08.570
of the Nieman
Foundation at Harvard,

00:07:08.570 --> 00:07:11.240
and in her six
years on campus, she

00:07:11.240 --> 00:07:14.900
has made the Nieman
program an integral part

00:07:14.900 --> 00:07:17.120
of Harvard's academic life.

00:07:17.120 --> 00:07:19.130
In planning this
year's Radcliffe day

00:07:19.130 --> 00:07:21.920
on the topic of
integrity and journalism,

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:25.760
I have benefited enormously
from Ann Marie's insight

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:27.230
and her generosity.

00:07:27.230 --> 00:07:30.440
She has been with me
every step of the way,

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:33.140
so I am delighted to
have her here today

00:07:33.140 --> 00:07:37.070
to introduce our panelists and
to moderate the discussion.

00:07:37.070 --> 00:07:40.400
But, before we dive into
our panel discussion,

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:42.770
we have a special treat.

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:45.650
As you know, this
afternoon we will honor

00:07:45.650 --> 00:07:47.900
Gwen Ifill and Judy Woodruff.

00:07:47.900 --> 00:07:50.990
Someone who has worked
closely with both of them

00:07:50.990 --> 00:07:54.260
is David Brooks, columnist
at the New York Times,

00:07:54.260 --> 00:07:57.650
and frequent guest
on the PBS NewsHour.

00:07:57.650 --> 00:07:59.900
Whatever the
medium, David always

00:07:59.900 --> 00:08:02.660
enlightens us with
his own unique angle

00:08:02.660 --> 00:08:05.090
on concerns of the moment.

00:08:05.090 --> 00:08:07.920
David has to be in
Washington, DC this afternoon.

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:11.390
He's actually going to hold
the fort at the PBS NewsHour,

00:08:11.390 --> 00:08:14.690
so he will not be able to
stay for the lunch program.

00:08:14.690 --> 00:08:16.940
But he did not
want this day to go

00:08:16.940 --> 00:08:22.010
by without adding his own
tribute to Gwen and to Judy.

00:08:22.010 --> 00:08:24.260
So when David finishes
his reflections,

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:26.210
Ann Marie will
introduce the panelists

00:08:26.210 --> 00:08:28.130
and we will begin
our discussion.

00:08:28.130 --> 00:08:30.800
Please join me now in
welcoming David to the podium.

00:08:49.261 --> 00:08:49.760
- Thank you.

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:51.843
I thought I'd try to impress
my boss by showing up

00:08:51.843 --> 00:08:52.550
to work today.

00:08:56.240 --> 00:09:03.100
Now, you should know, I teach
at Yale, and so I'll be brief.

00:09:03.100 --> 00:09:05.600
I know you Harvard people didn't
come here to hear me speak,

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:07.224
you came here to hear
yourselves speak.

00:09:11.770 --> 00:09:14.990
I will try to get out
of the way of that.

00:09:17.810 --> 00:09:20.750
I have a unique specialty.

00:09:20.750 --> 00:09:23.810
I go on Public Broadcasting
and I debate Catholics

00:09:23.810 --> 00:09:26.570
from Massachusetts.

00:09:26.570 --> 00:09:28.430
One of them on
NPR, is EJ Dionne,

00:09:28.430 --> 00:09:31.010
is sitting over there somewhere.

00:09:31.010 --> 00:09:34.670
And then, I do a segment on
the NewsHour with Mark Shields,

00:09:34.670 --> 00:09:36.440
our segment is called
Shields and Brooks.

00:09:36.440 --> 00:09:38.330
It should've been
called Brook Shields,

00:09:38.330 --> 00:09:41.420
but that wouldn't
have been better.

00:09:41.420 --> 00:09:43.220
My line about Mark,
is, he's been doing it

00:09:43.220 --> 00:09:44.810
for a little while,
that's the segment's now

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:45.650
Shields and Brooks.

00:09:45.650 --> 00:09:48.020
Before that, it was Shields
and [? Shego, ?] before

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:50.810
that, it was Shields and
Gergen and before that it was

00:09:50.810 --> 00:09:53.270
Shields and Coolidge, I think.

00:09:53.270 --> 00:09:55.890
It started out at Shields
and Thomas Aquinas,

00:09:55.890 --> 00:09:59.740
I think, it's a while ago.

00:09:59.740 --> 00:10:05.720
And we do have just
a very good time.

00:10:05.720 --> 00:10:08.690
The show always
lightens my spirit,

00:10:08.690 --> 00:10:13.130
and informs me, and makes
me feel a little better

00:10:13.130 --> 00:10:16.460
about America,
because of that show.

00:10:16.460 --> 00:10:20.990
Our audience skews a
little on the senior side.

00:10:20.990 --> 00:10:23.930
When a 93-year-old lady comes
up to me in the airport,

00:10:23.930 --> 00:10:26.690
I know what she's going to say,
it's I don't watch your show

00:10:26.690 --> 00:10:28.188
but my mother loves it.

00:10:35.920 --> 00:10:40.180
So I'll just give a few quick
remarks about Gwen and Judy.

00:10:40.180 --> 00:10:43.420
I have a group that I have
dinner with every Thursday

00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:44.050
night in DC.

00:10:44.050 --> 00:10:45.790
I've written a
column about them.

00:10:45.790 --> 00:10:48.790
And they're a bunch
of kids from DC,

00:10:48.790 --> 00:10:52.510
almost all African-American
kids 18 to 22,

00:10:52.510 --> 00:10:55.060
and they've had
rough backgrounds.

00:10:55.060 --> 00:10:58.240
And they all come to this
home where they can stay

00:10:58.240 --> 00:10:59.740
and where they get food.

00:10:59.740 --> 00:11:01.870
And we meet there
every Thursday,

00:11:01.870 --> 00:11:04.270
and we've been doing it
for about three years.

00:11:04.270 --> 00:11:06.820
And they're just on
the cusp of life.

00:11:06.820 --> 00:11:09.730
And what we give
them is, we adults

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:12.357
sit there and let them
show their talents to us

00:11:12.357 --> 00:11:13.690
and find themselves in that way.

00:11:13.690 --> 00:11:15.730
We provide them for an audience.

00:11:15.730 --> 00:11:18.610
What they give to us is
a complete intolerance

00:11:18.610 --> 00:11:20.452
of social distance.

00:11:20.452 --> 00:11:22.660
So I walk into this thing
the first time I went there

00:11:22.660 --> 00:11:25.540
three years ago and I met
a kid and his name was Ed

00:11:25.540 --> 00:11:28.156
and I reached out
to shake his hand,

00:11:28.156 --> 00:11:30.280
and he just said, we don't
really shake hands here,

00:11:30.280 --> 00:11:34.240
we hug here, and he sort
of embraced me in a hug

00:11:34.240 --> 00:11:39.430
and we've been hanging all
over each other ever since.

00:11:39.430 --> 00:11:43.300
And so, I was there last
night, with these kids,

00:11:43.300 --> 00:11:46.810
and it was just such a pleasure
to use time over dinner

00:11:46.810 --> 00:11:50.320
to talk about Gwen
and Judy and to tell,

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:53.290
sort of that generation,
a few things about how

00:11:53.290 --> 00:11:57.220
one can conduct one's life.

00:11:57.220 --> 00:12:00.799
And when I agreed to do this,
I thought Gwen would be here,

00:12:00.799 --> 00:12:02.590
and I was going to give
her a lot more crap

00:12:02.590 --> 00:12:05.380
than I'll be able to today.

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:07.510
But one of the things
I described to them

00:12:07.510 --> 00:12:09.520
was that on the day
Gwen died and Judy

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:12.820
called with the news I
went through my emails,

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:16.029
and I just looked at all
the emails she'd sent me.

00:12:16.029 --> 00:12:17.820
And some of them were
just check in emails,

00:12:17.820 --> 00:12:21.810
how you doin', you know, or
giving me some business about

00:12:21.810 --> 00:12:23.160
a column I'd written.

00:12:23.160 --> 00:12:26.130
But a surprising number
were surprisingly tough

00:12:26.130 --> 00:12:28.290
like, you need to learn
to communicate better,

00:12:28.290 --> 00:12:33.060
or, there were things that
I had let down the show.

00:12:33.060 --> 00:12:35.040
And her toughness
is one of the things

00:12:35.040 --> 00:12:38.057
that that leaps out at me.

00:12:38.057 --> 00:12:39.015
Toughness and tenacity.

00:12:39.015 --> 00:12:41.800
A tenacity we saw all
through the conventions,

00:12:41.800 --> 00:12:45.060
as she continued doing her
work, when she was much sicker

00:12:45.060 --> 00:12:47.620
than I, at least, knew.

00:12:47.620 --> 00:12:50.020
And so, she's at the end of
the spectrum on toughness

00:12:50.020 --> 00:12:52.970
and resilience, but
she's also on the end

00:12:52.970 --> 00:12:56.190
of the spectrum on kindness.

00:12:56.190 --> 00:13:00.030
And it's that odd combination
of those two things,

00:13:00.030 --> 00:13:03.300
extremely incandescent around
people at the same time

00:13:03.300 --> 00:13:06.370
toughness on behalf of craft.

00:13:06.370 --> 00:13:08.560
The love of people
is at the extreme,

00:13:08.560 --> 00:13:13.040
the dedication to craft,
the humility before God.

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:15.830
And so the thing I
wanted to talk to my kids

00:13:15.830 --> 00:13:20.830
about was, just what it is,
is a vocation, which, I think,

00:13:20.830 --> 00:13:23.620
if there's one thing that
Judy and Gwen represent,

00:13:23.620 --> 00:13:26.650
it's that quality of
having a vocation,

00:13:26.650 --> 00:13:30.260
and dedication to vocation.

00:13:30.260 --> 00:13:31.900
Frederick Bittner,
the novelist, once

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:35.140
wrote that a vocation is
where your deep gladness meets

00:13:35.140 --> 00:13:38.810
the world's deepest need and
it's the marriage of those two

00:13:38.810 --> 00:13:39.310
things.

00:13:39.310 --> 00:13:41.080
A career is something
you choose and you

00:13:41.080 --> 00:13:44.380
do as long as it's paying
off for you, but a vocation

00:13:44.380 --> 00:13:46.700
you're sort of summoned to.

00:13:46.700 --> 00:13:50.330
The great example is, Viktor
Frankl was a psychologist

00:13:50.330 --> 00:13:52.070
in Austria in the '30s.

00:13:52.070 --> 00:13:56.180
He was put in Auschwitz,
and he said, you know,

00:13:56.180 --> 00:13:59.120
we often tell people, what
do you want from life,

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:01.560
and he said that's
the wrong question.

00:14:01.560 --> 00:14:05.520
The right question is,
what is life asking of you.

00:14:05.520 --> 00:14:09.030
And I would say
for Gwen and Judy,

00:14:09.030 --> 00:14:12.510
life, and especially this
year, has asked them,

00:14:12.510 --> 00:14:16.380
and asked Judy now, to be
an anchor of a certain sort

00:14:16.380 --> 00:14:19.620
of news organization, which
I'll describe in a minute

00:14:19.620 --> 00:14:21.990
but which is a certain
sort of old fashioned news

00:14:21.990 --> 00:14:24.650
organization.

00:14:24.650 --> 00:14:30.790
A vocation requires a talent,
which Gwen and Judy have had.

00:14:30.790 --> 00:14:33.222
It reveals itself
through a pleasure.

00:14:33.222 --> 00:14:35.680
When you found your vocation
you get intrinsic pleasure out

00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:38.650
of doing those things,
and most of all

00:14:38.650 --> 00:14:40.900
it expresses itself
through a consistency

00:14:40.900 --> 00:14:44.220
of commitment over time.

00:14:44.220 --> 00:14:46.250
A commitment is falling
in love with something

00:14:46.250 --> 00:14:48.470
and then building a structure
of behavior around it

00:14:48.470 --> 00:14:52.090
for those moments
when love falters.

00:14:52.090 --> 00:14:54.970
And so, when I think
about the NewsHour

00:14:54.970 --> 00:14:59.020
and especially Gwen's commitment
to it and now Judy's, what

00:14:59.020 --> 00:15:03.770
I think about is consistency
over time and permanence.

00:15:03.770 --> 00:15:08.240
When I think of Judy, I
think of her writing notes

00:15:08.240 --> 00:15:13.100
furiously before a segment,
through the afternoon

00:15:13.100 --> 00:15:15.400
and through the mornings.

00:15:15.400 --> 00:15:18.040
Judy's been in this
business a while

00:15:18.040 --> 00:15:20.350
and it would be easy to coast.

00:15:20.350 --> 00:15:22.480
Television is an
industry in which

00:15:22.480 --> 00:15:28.000
coasting is supremely easy
and supremely alluring.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.570
And yet I've never seen her
come anything less than 300%

00:15:31.570 --> 00:15:34.790
prepared for any segment
we've been doing.

00:15:34.790 --> 00:15:37.030
And so, it is that
consistency and permanence

00:15:37.030 --> 00:15:40.300
over time that I think
is what's so emblematic,

00:15:40.300 --> 00:15:44.340
and that's what I so much
wanted to talk to my kids about.

00:15:44.340 --> 00:15:49.950
And then permanence and
consistency in what we do.

00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:51.940
The NewsHour is
not just a program,

00:15:51.940 --> 00:15:55.920
it's an institution, and those
of us who come to work there,

00:15:55.920 --> 00:15:58.800
it was there before
we came, and I hope

00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:01.740
and pray it will be there
long after we're gone.

00:16:01.740 --> 00:16:03.720
And when you come
to the NewsHour,

00:16:03.720 --> 00:16:07.860
you come and try to inhabit
certain standards of behavior.

00:16:07.860 --> 00:16:11.580
For the first 10 years I did
it, the host was Jim Lehrer,

00:16:11.580 --> 00:16:14.910
and when I would say
something good on the program,

00:16:14.910 --> 00:16:18.080
his eyes would crinkle
with a little pleasure,

00:16:18.080 --> 00:16:21.165
and when I said something
bad his mouth would turn down

00:16:21.165 --> 00:16:24.200
in a little displeasure.

00:16:24.200 --> 00:16:26.360
And so, I learned how
to do this business

00:16:26.360 --> 00:16:29.370
by trying to avoid the mouth
turn down and get the eye

00:16:29.370 --> 00:16:31.180
crinkle.

00:16:31.180 --> 00:16:33.850
And so, there's certain
standards that no one even

00:16:33.850 --> 00:16:36.610
has to express, that
are inherent in walking

00:16:36.610 --> 00:16:38.520
in the place.

00:16:38.520 --> 00:16:41.370
And Jim and Robbins
started it, Gwen and Judy

00:16:41.370 --> 00:16:44.910
have continued it, and I
think we all have a sensation

00:16:44.910 --> 00:16:47.070
now that somehow
the NewsHour has

00:16:47.070 --> 00:16:50.286
found its moment in this year.

00:16:50.286 --> 00:16:51.660
Not only in the
ratings, which we

00:16:51.660 --> 00:16:58.340
don't care about, but
in the value of doing

00:16:58.340 --> 00:17:02.120
the permanent, long-standing
traditional things in an era

00:17:02.120 --> 00:17:04.910
where impermanence
and attention-deficit

00:17:04.910 --> 00:17:07.750
are becoming the norm.

00:17:07.750 --> 00:17:11.650
And so, something stable,
and solid, and permanent,

00:17:11.650 --> 00:17:14.619
and old-fashioned,
and counter-cultural,

00:17:14.619 --> 00:17:18.130
somehow becomes a pillar in a
moment when a lot of pillars

00:17:18.130 --> 00:17:20.720
are being washed away.

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:25.550
And so, basically, I just
talked to the kids about all

00:17:25.550 --> 00:17:28.339
these things, about
permanence, about institutions,

00:17:28.339 --> 00:17:33.130
about vocations, about
the love of people,

00:17:33.130 --> 00:17:36.340
and then just to round it
off I took out my phone

00:17:36.340 --> 00:17:39.610
and I took out a big
picture of Gwen on my phone.

00:17:39.610 --> 00:17:43.150
And after Gwen died when people
were eulogizing her the one

00:17:43.150 --> 00:17:45.640
thing every eulogy
and every obituary

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:49.720
had was about the
quality of her smile.

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:52.390
And the words were,
incandescent, luminescent,

00:17:52.390 --> 00:17:54.780
lit from within.

00:17:54.780 --> 00:17:57.140
And I don't know what creates
that kind of incandescence

00:17:57.140 --> 00:18:00.920
and luminescence, but taking
pleasure in the small things

00:18:00.920 --> 00:18:04.550
and in the people, combined
with that ferocious dedication

00:18:04.550 --> 00:18:09.440
to the integrity of craft
was what marked her,

00:18:09.440 --> 00:18:11.190
and which marks
the program today,

00:18:11.190 --> 00:18:13.970
which I think a lot of us are so
proud to be in the same country

00:18:13.970 --> 00:18:14.530
with.

00:18:14.530 --> 00:18:15.029
Thank you.

00:18:53.860 --> 00:18:59.470
- Many, many thanks to David
Brooks for those comments,

00:18:59.470 --> 00:19:04.810
and also for the work that
he, and Judy, and, Gwen,

00:19:04.810 --> 00:19:07.600
have so thoughtfully
done, for so long,

00:19:07.600 --> 00:19:11.350
on the NewsHour I think you'd
all agree that, together, they

00:19:11.350 --> 00:19:16.240
offered us some of the
smartest political analysis

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:21.850
of the recent election season
and post election season

00:19:21.850 --> 00:19:28.000
and I am abundantly grateful
for him and for that.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:29.620
OK, enough about
the guy from Yale.

00:19:33.040 --> 00:19:36.770
I am so honored
to be here today,

00:19:36.770 --> 00:19:41.500
and especially want to thank
Dean Cohen for including me

00:19:41.500 --> 00:19:44.530
in this very, very
important conversation,

00:19:44.530 --> 00:19:48.850
and also to thank her
for her prescience.

00:19:48.850 --> 00:19:52.900
If anything, her notion
to honor Judy and Gwen

00:19:52.900 --> 00:19:55.810
and explore the
theme of untruths

00:19:55.810 --> 00:20:00.580
and their consequences, is
more urgent, and relevant,

00:20:00.580 --> 00:20:04.310
and smarter today, than when she
first broached it a year ago,

00:20:04.310 --> 00:20:08.650
so we all owe her
a lot of gratitude

00:20:08.650 --> 00:20:12.700
for even conceiving
of this idea.

00:20:12.700 --> 00:20:14.470
It seemed like an
issue at the time

00:20:14.470 --> 00:20:16.790
but, boy, is it an issue now.

00:20:16.790 --> 00:20:18.560
So thank you so much for that.

00:20:26.190 --> 00:20:29.720
And as President Faust very
recently reminded our Fellows

00:20:29.720 --> 00:20:31.850
at the Nieman Foundation
for Journalism

00:20:31.850 --> 00:20:35.450
in a so-called
post-truth environment,

00:20:35.450 --> 00:20:38.840
the issues bearing on
the media are precisely

00:20:38.840 --> 00:20:42.290
those faced by the academy
certainly here at Harvard,

00:20:42.290 --> 00:20:44.390
where the motto is veritas.

00:20:44.390 --> 00:20:48.080
So, I think that what we'll
be dealing with today,

00:20:48.080 --> 00:20:51.260
both celebrating,
and concerned about,

00:20:51.260 --> 00:20:56.270
has such direct ties to
what we do here every day.

00:20:56.270 --> 00:21:01.100
It is no exaggeration to say
that, for many in my industry,

00:21:01.100 --> 00:21:04.160
Gwen and Judy are heroes.

00:21:04.160 --> 00:21:07.730
Two women who join forces
to create a, sort of,

00:21:07.730 --> 00:21:10.680
journalistic true north.

00:21:10.680 --> 00:21:13.650
Through their work
individually, and together, they

00:21:13.650 --> 00:21:16.950
have not only personified
our highest values,

00:21:16.950 --> 00:21:18.600
but defined them.

00:21:18.600 --> 00:21:21.360
In what has been a
remarkably challenging year,

00:21:21.360 --> 00:21:24.900
the NewsHour has
offered us everything we

00:21:24.900 --> 00:21:27.660
ask of journalism done right.

00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:31.410
On a personal note, I would also
like to publicly acknowledge

00:21:31.410 --> 00:21:34.950
my great debt to Gwen who is
on the search committee that

00:21:34.950 --> 00:21:39.700
brought me to Harvard, so
I am very grateful to her.

00:21:42.850 --> 00:21:46.680
We are so privileged to have
four extraordinary panelists

00:21:46.680 --> 00:21:48.540
with us, this morning,
to try and help

00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:51.510
us make sense of this
interesting and complicated

00:21:51.510 --> 00:21:52.620
time.

00:21:52.620 --> 00:21:54.540
They offer a diversity
of experience,

00:21:54.540 --> 00:21:56.250
and perspective,
which we will hear

00:21:56.250 --> 00:21:59.100
reflected in their remarks.

00:21:59.100 --> 00:22:03.000
A little bit about format, I
will do brief introductions

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:08.610
of them all next, and then
